<div class="prose">

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">Quick orientation</div>
  Three strands. Three separate scores per assessment, reported as a triplet (e.g. <strong>K/U 7 · T/T 6 · C 7</strong>). Each on the 1–8 band scale. Scores are not summed — the triplet <em>is</em> the grade.
</div>

<h2>The three strands at a glance</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Strand</th><th>In one sentence</th><th>The move that gets you to 7–8</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>K/U — Knowledge & Understanding</strong></td>
      <td>You know the framework (OPVL, the AI Documentation Template, discipline vocabulary) and you apply it accurately.</td>
      <td>Use discipline-specific vocabulary precisely throughout. Get every OPVL letter for every source. Fill the AI Documentation Template completely.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>T/T — Thinking & Transfer</strong></td>
      <td>You apply the framework critically — to unfamiliar sources, to AI, to engineering trade-offs — and notice things others miss.</td>
      <td>Identify <em>specific</em> limitations (not generic ones). Name a specific thing the AI got wrong, with evidence. Surface non-obvious agreements and disagreements across sources.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>C — Communication</strong></td>
      <td>You make your reasoning clear to a peer audience in the format the assignment expects.</td>
      <td>Logical structure, ideas fully developed and concise, vocabulary precise. Citations integrated (not just listed). Defense well-paced; Q&amp;A substantive.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<div class="callout warn">
  <div class="callout-title">Two gates that cap your score</div>
  <p><strong>K/U gate.</strong> Missing or trivially-completed <a href="/student-hub/ai-documentation-template/">AI Documentation Template</a> caps K/U at 3–4 regardless of the rest of the work.</p>
  <p><strong>T/T gate.</strong> If you can't identify a specific thing the AI got wrong, T/T caps at 5–6 regardless of how strong your traditional-source OPVL is.</p>
</div>

<h2>Bands at a glance</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Band</th><th>What it looks like (across all three strands)</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>7–8 Exemplary</strong></td>
      <td>Thorough, specific, precise. Vocabulary used naturally. Limitations are real and specific. AI documentation complete. Communication clear and well-paced.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>5–6 Proficient</strong></td>
      <td>Substantially right with minor gaps. Vocabulary mostly precise. Limitations real but a bit generic in places. Documentation substantially complete. Communication clear with minor unevenness.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>3–4 Developing</strong></td>
      <td>Some understanding, with patterns of weakness. Vocabulary inconsistent. Limitations skew generic ("this source might be biased"). Documentation partial. Communication structure attempted but uneven.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>1–2 Limited</strong></td>
      <td>Multiple major elements missing. Vocabulary absent or misused. AI treated as just another reliable source. Documentation missing or trivial. Communication lacks structure.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Need more detail?</h2>

<p>The <a href="/foundations/the-rubric/">full Rubric page</a> in Foundations has the band descriptors broken out per strand — the specific things examiners look for at each band on K/U vs. T/T vs. C separately. Use this Quick Reference while you work; use the full Rubric when you're calibrating or appealing a score.</p>

</div>
